EPDM rubber membrane is a synthetic waterproofing material made from ethylene propylene diene monomer rubber, widely used for flat and low-slope roofs, ponds, basements, and other applications requiring long-term, flexible waterproofing. It is valued for its exceptional elasticity, allowing it to stretch and recover without cracking, which makes it highly resistant to thermal movement, structural settlement, and vibration. EPDM membranes are typically supplied in large sheets, reducing the number of seams and potential leak points, and joints are sealed using adhesives or specialized tapes rather than heat welding. The material has excellent resistance to ultraviolet radiation, ozone, weathering, and temperature extremes, often achieving service lives of 30â€“50 years with minimal maintenance. EPDM is lightweight, easy to install, and compatible with a wide range of substrates, though careful detailing around penetrations and edges is essential for optimal performance. From an environmental perspective, EPDM has good durability and low maintenance demands, contributing to long-term sustainability despite being a synthetic material. Overall, EPDM rubber membranes are considered one of the most reliable and durable waterproofing solutions for modern roofing and building envelope systems.